{"author":{"id":"4f324cb92ea8becbd20298a5cb00d036d7c89b32eed2fdf62a9c7332d3e57157"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1783008425,"nonce":"DkdmbyOUpyd+fzC5iiEodtyIHUc=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOOEv6_s8AAAABIiR8nw","github-url":"https://github.com/graphcore-research/gwr/issues/217#issuecomment-4867783839"},"message":"I think the apparent memory growth is an artefact of using `BatchSize::SmallInput`.\n\nThese benchmarks create a fresh `Engine` in the setup function. With `SmallInput`, Criterion batches setup values before running them, so it can temporarily hold many `Engine` instances at once. That makes RSS climb and look leak-like. The memory does eventually plateau or taper off, but only after a much longer run.\n\nChanging the engine-based benchmarks to `BatchSize::PerIteration` makes Criterion create, run, and drop each benchmark input before creating the next one. With that change, RSS reaches a lower steady range much sooner.\n\nThe attached chart compares `SmallInput` and `PerIteration` RSS over time.\n\n\u003cimg width=\"1700\" height=\"1020\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/cbbd3698-1d50-458b-95ec-b09aaf6c1408\" /\u003e","files":null},{"type":3,"timestamp":1783090374,"nonce":"8HzBQpq4/ntf4nyDFraq72y0E/A=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOOEv6_s8AAAABIrfAKQ","github-url":"https://github.com/graphcore-research/gwr/issues/217#issuecomment-4877434921"},"message":"Waiting on @samchesney to confirm he's happy with this.","files":null}]}